//@ compile-fail
//@ error-contains: has no order
//
// A generic body is typechecked once, with `T` abstract, so there is no concrete type
// to ask whether it can be ordered. Allowing `<` anyway is what the old compiler did,
// and it monomorphised into a comparison of two pointers for any type without a
// structural order — a silent wrong answer.
//
// So the bound is required: write `where T: Ord` and the body is allowed, with each
// call site checking the type actually supplied. See marker_ord_bound.neon.

use std::io;

fn max[T](a: T, b: T) -> T {
    if a < b { b } else { a }
}

fn main() {
    io::println("#{max(1, 2)}");
}
